    <div xml:id="PN257">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>ceruppiṭaic ciṟupara laṉṉaṉ kaṇaikkā</l>
<l>lavvayiṟ ṟakaṉṟa mārpiṟ paiṅkaṭ</l>
<l>kucci ṉiraitta kurūumayir mōvāyc</l>
<l>ceviyiṟantu tāḻtaruṅ kavuḷaṉ villō</l>
<l>ṭiyārkolō vaḷiyaṉ ṟāṉē tēri</l>
<l>ṉūrperi tikantaṉṟu milaṉē yaraṇeṉak</l>
<l>kāṭukaik koṇṭaṉṟu milaṉē kālaip</l>
<l>pullā riṉanirai celpuṟa nōkkik</l>
<l>kaiyiṟ cuṭṭip paiyeṉa veṇṇic</l>
<l>cilaiyiṉ māṟṟi yōṉē yavaitā</l>
<l>mikappala vāyiṉu meṉṉā meṉaittum</l>
<l>veṇkō ṭōṉṟāk kuḻiciyoṭu</l>
<l>nāḷuṟai mattoli kēḷā tōṉē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>He who is like one with little pebbles in [his] sandals, with round legs,</l>
<l>a pretty belly, a wide chest, green eyes,</l>
<l>from whose cheeks a beard with glossy hair arranged</l>
<l>like Kuccu grass falls down, going beyond the ears, with a bow</l>
<l>– who [is he]? Ah, poor man! If you seek [him],</l>
<l>[normally] he would not much go beyond the village</l>
<l>and he would not take hold of the wilderness as [his] fortification,</l>
<l>he who, looking at the moving backs of the grass-eating herds in the morning,</l>
<l>pointing [them] out with [his] hands, quietly counting them,</l>
<l>bartered [them] with [his] bow. Those, </l>
<l>even if they are very many, what is it</l>
<l>to him who did not hear the sound of the churning stick that lasts the day,</l>
<l>along with the pot in which none of the white yield appeared?  </l>
</lg>
    </div>
